==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trapezoid
<hw>Trap"e*zoid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/
trapezoid-shaped; <?/ table + <?/ shape, likeness: cf. F.
<ets>trap⟦eacute⟧zo⟦ium⟧de</ets>. See <er>Trapezium</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A plane four-sided figure, having
two sides parallel to each other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A bone of the carpus at the base
of the second metacarpal, or index finger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trapezoid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trapezoid
<hw>Trap"e*zoid</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the form of
a trapezoid; trapezoidal; <as>as, the <ex>trapezoid</ex> ligament which
connects the coracoid process and the clavicle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the trapezoid
ligament; <as>as, the <ex>trapezoid</ex> line</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trapezoidal</ent>⟦br⟧
